# =============================================================================
# README
# =============================================================================
#
# This is the per-repo .gitignore template for archAssimilator projects.
#
#
# WHAT THIS FILE IS
# -----------------
# It's a template — a starting point you copy into each new project. Think
# of it like a form with optional sections.
#
# Every line in this top section starts with #, which means Git completely
# ignores it. It's just notes for you (or anyone else on the team). It's
# here so that six months from now, if you open the file and think "what's
# going on here?", the answer is right in front of you.
#
#
# WHAT WE'VE DONE
# ----------------
# A global .gitignore has been installed at ~/.gitignore_global and
# registered with Git using:
#
#   git config --global core.excludesfile ~/.gitignore_global
#
# That global file already handles:
#
#   - macOS artefacts       (.DS_Store, ._*, .Spotlight-V100, .Trashes, etc.)
#   - Cursor                (.cursor/, .cursorignore, .cursorindexingignore)
#   - JetBrains IDEs        (.idea/, *.iml, *.iws, etc.)
#   - VS Code               (.vscode/, *.code-workspace)
#   - Sublime Text          (*.sublime-project, *.sublime-workspace)
#   - Vim / Neovim          (*.swp, *.swo, *~, tags, etc.)
#   - Emacs                 (*~, \#*\#, .emacs.desktop, etc.)
#   - Environment files     (.env, .env.* — but NOT .env.example/.env.template)
#   - Common build output   (node_modules/, __pycache__/, build/, dist/, etc.)
#   - Terraform             (.terraform/, *.tfstate, etc.)
#   - Windows/Linux clutter (Thumbs.db, Desktop.ini, .directory, etc.)
#
# Because all of the above is handled globally, you never need to repeat
# any of those entries in this file.
#
#
# THE COMMENTED-OUT SECTIONS BELOW
# ---------------------------------
# Further down this file you'll see blocks for Python, JavaScript, Java,
# Go, Rust, and so on. Every line in those blocks also starts with #,
# which means they are currently switched off — Git is not paying
# attention to them.
#
# When you start a new project, you decide which language or framework
# you are using and then delete the # at the start of each line in that
# section. That "switches it on."
#
# For example, if you are writing a Python project, you would change
# this:
#
#   # *.pyc
#   # __pycache__/
#   # .venv/
#
# to this:
#
#   *.pyc
#   __pycache__/
#   .venv/
#
# Now Git knows to ignore those Python files. You leave all the other
# language sections alone (still switched off) because they don't apply
# to that project.
#
#
# WHY NOT JUST SWITCH EVERYTHING ON?
# ------------------------------------
# Because different languages produce different junk files. A Python
# project will never generate .class files (that's Java), and a Java
# project will never generate __pycache__/ folders (that's Python).
# Ignoring things that don't exist is harmless but makes the file
# cluttered and confusing. Cleaner to only activate what you actually
# need.
#
#
# THE SHORT VERSION
# ------------------
# 1. Copy this file into the root of your new repo.
# 2. Find the section that matches your programming language.
# 3. Delete the # from the start of each line in that section.
# 4. Add any project-specific entries at the bottom.
# 5. That's it. You're done.
#
#
# Date: 260314
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Python
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# *.pyc
# *.pyo
# *.egg
# *.egg-info/
# __pycache__/
# .venv/
# venv/
# .mypy_cache/
# .pytest_cache/
# .ruff_cache/
# htmlcov/
# *.cover

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# JavaScript / TypeScript (Node.js)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# node_modules/
# .next/
# .nuxt/
# .output/
# .turbo/
# *.tsbuildinfo
# .eslintcache
# .parcel-cache/

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Java / Kotlin / Gradle / Maven
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# target/
# *.class
# *.jar
# *.war
# *.ear
# .gradle/
# build/
# !gradle-wrapper.jar

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Go
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# bin/
# vendor/
# *.exe
# *.test
# *.out

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Rust
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# target/
# Cargo.lock
# **/*.rs.bk

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# C / C++
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# *.o
# *.obj
# *.so
# *.dylib
# *.a
# *.exe
# *.out
# cmake-build-*/

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .NET / C#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# bin/
# obj/
# *.suo
# *.user
# *.userosscache
# *.sln.docstates
# packages/

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
